# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: criticism-of-mcdonald-s
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] On August 10, 1993, a shooting occurred at a McDonald’s restaurant in Kenosha, Wisconsin, United States.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] At 1:30 am CDT, 25-year-old Dion Terres walked into the McDonald's restaurant with a .44 Magnum revolver and killed two people and injured a third before committing suicide.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] The attack occurred a month after the ninth anniversary of the 1984 San Ysidro McDonald's massacre and 15 months after the 1992 Sydney River McDonald's murders.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] There were 20-30 employees and customers in the restaurant at the time the attack took place.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] On August 10, 1993, Dion Terres, dressed in military fatigues, drove his 1989 Chevrolet Cavalier from his home to the McDonald's restaurant at 7530 Pershing Rd., arriving at around 1:30 p.m.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] While getting out his car with his Colt AR-15 rifle in hand, Terres accidentally locked himself out of his car, leaving a loaded 30-round magazine for the rifle on the passenger seat; police later discovered another 30-round magazine in his breast pocket.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] According to the Kenosha County deputy chief medical examiner, Terres had marijuana in his system at the time of the shooting, but it was not possible to tell if Terres had smoked marijuana shortly before the attack or had ingested it as long as a month earlier.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] Terres yelled at everyone to leave the restaurant before he first shot Bruce Bojesen in the head, killing him instantly, then shot and wounded both Sandra Kenaga in the abdomen and Kirk Hauptmann in the wrist.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] After shooting the victims, Terres shot fatally himself through the mouth.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] Dion Terres (October 2, 1967 – August 10, 1993) was a 25-year-old male from Arlington Heights, Illinois.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] After he graduated from John Hersey High School in Arlington Heights in 1986, he reportedly bragged to former classmates about joining the military, though investigations later revealed he never actually served.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] Terres moved to Kenosha from Arlington Heights in September 1992, about 11 months prior to the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] He was previously a cellular phone assembler at a Motorola manufacturing plant in Libertyville, Illinois, but in March 1993, he was terminated from his job after failing to show up to work for three consecutive days without explanation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] Shortly after in March 1993, he bought the Colt AR-15 rifle at Eagle Training Gun Shop in Kenosha.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] Terres previously bought the Smith & Wesson Model 629 .44 Magnum revolver in 1989 at Maxon Shooters Supply in Mount Prospect, Illinois.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] According to his ex-girlfriend, 16-year-old Kimberly Sinkler, A few days before the shooting, Terres had become enraged when a Jehovah's Witness missionary came to his door.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] He threatened to shoot the man, then ran upstairs, jumped into his fatigues and dashed back downstairs brandishing his rifle.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] By the time he reached the door, the missionary had left.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] After the shooting, Terres was looked into as a possible suspect in the Brown's Chicken massacre that happened on January 8, 1993 in Palatine, Illinois.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/1993-kenosha-mcdonald-s-shooting] Police conclude that no link had been made to connect Terres to the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] On 22 July 2016, a mass shooting classified as a right-wing extremist attack occurred in the vicinity of the Olympia shopping mall in the Moosach district of Munich, Germany.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The perpetrator, 18-year-old Iranian-German David Sonboly, opened fire on teenagers with migrant background at a McDonald's restaurant before shooting at bystanders in the street outside and then in the mall itself.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Nine people were killed – most of them with immigrant backgrounds – and 36 others were injured, four of them by gunfire.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly, who had been influenced by far-right ideology, xenophobia, and racist beliefs, hid nearby for more than two hours and killed himself by a self-inflicted gunshot wound when confronted by police.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Later investigations determined that the attack was politically motivated and driven by right-wing extremist views.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Germany's security agency described him as a "psychologically ill avenger".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] An independent report by three political scientists said Sonboly may also have been driven by xenophobia or far-right ideology.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] *Der Spiegel* reported in 2016 that fellow online video gamers said that Sonboly wrote anti-Turkish messages, admired Germany's right-wing AfD party, and was "very nationalistic".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] According to media reports, some of those who knew him said he considered himself part of the Aryan race, and boasted about sharing the same birthday as Adolf Hitler.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In the light of this, several politicians urged the police to focus on his possible political motives and in 2019 Bavarian police declared that the shooting was partly motivated by far-right extremism.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The attack took place on the fifth anniversary of the 2011 Norway attacks.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] On the evening of 22 July 2016, David Sonboly opened fire at a McDonald's restaurant near the Olympia shopping mall in the Moosach district of Munich.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Despite initial reports of multiple attack sites, police could not confirm attacks in any locations other than the shopping area.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly had made a fake Facebook account with a girl's name and posted four invitations to come to the restaurant, but "none of the addressees apparently complied".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He stayed in the restaurant from about 5pm.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] At about 5:50pm, he went into the restaurant's toilets on the first floor, and left a manifesto on his laptop.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] About eight minutes later he left the toilets and opened fire on a group of six teenagers sitting at a table, killing five and wounding another, using a handgun he had taken from his backpack.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He immediately left the restaurant, turned to the right and began shooting at people fleeing towards an electronics shop and at two vehicles parked there.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He fired sixteen bullets in this area, killing three people and wounding three others.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly then crossed Hanauer Strasse and slowly walked into the shopping mall, where he fatally shot another teenager near the lifts.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] At about 6:00pm, Sonboly walked from the shopping mall, over a covered footbridge to the adjoining multi-storey car park.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] While on this bridge, he fired shots towards the parking deck and a passer-by, but hurt no one.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He fired thirteen rounds at two unoccupied parked vehicles and walked onto the top parking deck.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] There, Sonboly had an argument with a man who shouted at him from the balcony of his flat.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] During this argument, Sonboly fired two shots at the man.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Another man, who was also on his balcony, was wounded by ricocheting bullet fragments.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly fired three more times towards the mall and towards an employee, without hurting anyone.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Police officers spotted the gunman from an outdoor balcony of the mall, and one officer fired a shot from a submachine gun at him, but missed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly ran across Riesstrasse and hid in a residential area.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He tried to get into a house, and lingered in a stairwell, where he had contact with residents.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] At 18:26, he went outside and was confronted by police officers, whereupon he fatally shot himself in the head.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] An early witness, identified only by her first name Lauretta, in talking to CNN correspondent Doug McConnell on the phone claimed that the gunman had shouted "*Allahu Akbar*!" The woman's account has not been verified by other witnesses or the police, though it was widely disseminated in the media.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] A video distributed online showed a gunman firing at pedestrians outside McDonald's.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He then moved on to the shopping mall itself.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Another video showed the gunman walking alone on the roof of a nearby car park before opening fire again.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He was heard shouting "I am German" (**Ich bin Deutscher**) and "I was born here" (**Ich bin hier geboren**) after an onlooker shouted anti-Turkish statements and other abuse at him.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] According to *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung*, the gunman also shouted back "Fucking Turks".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] However, it is still not clear who started the anti-Turkish insults.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] An urgent warning was issued to avoid the Karlsplatz ("Stachus"), due to reports of multiple shootings occurring there.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Munich police had received information about an attack at Karlsplatz, but after arriving there, announced that the information was false.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Drivers were advised not to pick up any passengers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] People in Munich were warned by the police to stay at home and avoid crowds and public squares.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Following initial reports of shots being fired, some 2,300 officers were deployed throughout Munich from the greater area and surrounding states.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Munich police urged residents not to leave their homes until further notice.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The special operations police unit GSG 9 was deployed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Other regions of Germany, Austria, and Switzerland were asked to assist in the investigation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] A backpack was found apparently matching the one carried by the gunman at McDonald's.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Police reportedly used a robot to examine it, and a total of 300 rounds of ammunition were found inside.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Police officials warned of "an acute terror situation" and initially thought that there were up to three attackers, but later confirmed that there was only one gunman.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Munich U-Bahn, tram service, bus service, and services on the central portion of the S-Bahn in Munich were stopped.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Munich main station was evacuated and all trains were cancelled in and out of Munich.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Regional and inter-city trains ceased their service to and from the region of the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Deutsche Bahn provided accommodation trains for stranded commuters and tourists where they could seek refuge.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] These were located at Mammendorf, Starnberg, Geltendorf, Dachau, and Freising.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Nine victims and the perpetrator died in the incident; 16 others were injured, four by gunshot.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Three of the dead were female, and six were male.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Three of the victims were Turkish, two victims were from German Sinti families and one was from a Kosovan Roma family.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] There have been claims that Sonboly deliberately targeted people of Turkish or Arab origin, groups he apparently felt had picked on him at school.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The state government initially said the victims were not chosen in any particular way and that Sonboly did not know any of them.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Police initially considered it a coincidence that all of the fatalities were of immigrant backgrounds; they suggested this may be because the McDonald's was frequented by the children of immigrants.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In preparation for admitting the injured, multiple hospitals called their medical staff in to work outside normal working hours.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] A state of emergency was declared at the Rechts der Isar Hospital, where one of the injured victims died.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Munich police chief Hubertus Andrä said that the shooting appeared to be a "classic shooting rampage" and not terrorism.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Police said that the gunman was obsessed with mass shootings and that written material on such attacks was found in his room.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Prosecutor Steinkraus Koch said that the gunman had a book about school shootings called *Why Kids Kill: Inside the Minds of School Shooters* by Peter F.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] No references to religion were found in documents in his home.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Andrä said that there was an "obvious" link between the shooting and the fifth anniversary of the 2011 Norway attacks committed by Anders Behring Breivik.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] However, a police search of the shooter's residence did not find the manifesto written and distributed by Breivik.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] According to *Abendzeitung*, the shooter's own manifesto was found on his computer's hard disk.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Police investigator Robert Heimberger said that the shooter appeared to have hacked a girl's Facebook account in an attempt to lure people to McDonald's with an offer of free food, but it was later suspected that he had in fact simply created a fake Facebook account, not hacked an existing one.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Authorities said that the gunman had been planning the shooting for a year and probably purchased his gun illegally on the darknet.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] It was said to be a "reactivated" Glock 17 9mm semi-automatic pistol that previously had been used as a theatre prop.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] German police believe that the gun may have originated in Slovakia, and said that its serial number had been removed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] On 25 July 2016, Munich police announced the arrest of a 16-year-old Afghan friend of the perpetrator who was being investigated on suspicion of failing to report the gunman's plans.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Nearly two years after the shooting, police opened an investigation into Sonboly's contact with William Atchison, perpetrator of the 2017 Aztec High School shooting, and with a boy in Gerlingen who planned a school shooting there.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Shortly after the Munich shooting, Atchison wrote an epitaph to Sonboly on Encyclopedia Dramatica, calling him a "true Aryan" and "true German".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] German Interior Minister Thomas de Maizière said that he was the son of Shiite Muslims from Iran who came to Germany as asylum seekers in the 1990s.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly's parents told police that their son had possibly converted to Christianity, but that he was not religious.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In May 2016, Sonboly had his first name changed in all official documents from *Ali* to *David*.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The shooting was initially theorized to be linked to Islamic extremism, as one report said he said "Allahu akbar" but was proven false.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution, Germany's security agency, also believed he was a "psychologically ill avenger" rather than a terrorist.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly had undergone psychiatric treatment for depression, anxiety and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In 2015, he had been treated for two months as an inpatient in a mental care facility.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He was largely isolated from his peers and suffered years of bullying by classmates, which included physical abuse.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] A former classmate recalled, "We always "mobbed" [*sic*] him in school, and he always told us that he would kill us".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He developed a hatred for those of a similar age and background as those who bullied him, mainly Turks and Albanians.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He developed an "irrational worldview" in which he believed that the people he hated were infected with a virus and must be exterminated.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] On the day of the shooting, Sonboly saved a document on his computer in which he wrote "The bullying will be paid back today".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] During the shooting itself, he shouted that he had been bullied for seven years.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly had an obsession with mass shootings and rampage killers; he compiled a scrapbook of news clippings on mass shootings and owned several books on the subject.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] During his psychiatric treatment he repeatedly told fellow patients to refer to him as the 'Spree Killer'.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] One incident that fascinated him was the Winnenden school shooting, and he visited Winnenden and took pictures there.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly was also fascinated by the 2011 Norway attacks perpetrated by Norwegian terrorist Anders Behring Breivik, and Sonboly's shooting was on its fifth anniversary.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Sonboly voiced xenophobic views and support for the far-right.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] *Der Spiegel* reported that fellow online video gamers said that Sonboly wrote anti-Turkish messages, admired Germany's right-wing AfD party, and was "very nationalistic".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In light of this, several politicians urged the police to focus on his possible political motives.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In October 2017, a panel of three political scientists commissioned by Munich City Council concluded that Sonboly's shooting was partially driven by xenophobia and far-right ideology.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Investigators, however, argued that his xenophobia stemmed from being bullied by other immigrants.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Bavarian State Office of Criminal Investigation commissioned another report into Sonboly's motives.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In 2018, it concluded that the incident was a non-political shooting rampage driven by bullying, romantic rejection, and obsession with other mass shootings.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] In October 2019, it was announced by the Bavarian police that the shooting was now also classified as a "politically motivated crime" that "was at least partly motivated by the right-wing extremist views of the perpetrator".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Bavarian State Police urged the public not to publish online any photos or videos of the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] They provided a special upload platform which allowed witnesses to upload photos, audio, or video recordings directly in order to assist the investigation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Munich residents also used the Twitter hashtag #*offeneTür* (open door) to tell people in need of shelter where they could go.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] German Chancellor Angela Merkel addressed the victims' families in a press conference on 23 July by saying, "We suffer with you." She thanked the Munich residents who opened their doors for stranded people.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Minister-President of Bavaria, Horst Seehofer, urged extreme caution against drawing premature conclusions and noted that optimisation of the security forces had to be considered.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] He said that he had spent more than four hours in the operations centre on 22 July, and thanked the forces for acting with professionalism and calm.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Interior Minister of Bavaria, Joachim Herrmann, announced an investigation into why there had been numerous false alarms.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The German Depression-Help Trust (*Stiftung Deutsche Depressionshilfe*) warned of stigmatizing mentally ill people in reaction to the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] After the shooter was revealed to have been born in Germany, the right-wing politician André Poggenburg was condemned and mocked in German media for having previously blamed Merkel's open refugee policy for the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Department of State warned Americans in Munich to "shelter in place".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] President Barack Obama said in a statement that he pledged support for those affected by the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Czech Interior Minister Milan Chovanec said his country would reinforce its borders to prevent the perpetrator(s) from fleeing into that country, according to German television station n-tv.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Czech Foreign Ministry set up an emergency hotline and urged Czechs to avoid public places.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Iranian Ministry of Foreign Affairs condemned the attack.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] The Ministry's spokesperson, Bahram Ghassemi, expressed condolences to the German government and nation, saying, "The killing of innocent and defenseless civilians has marked another blot on the human history".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2016-munich-shooting] Greek Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras said that having a Greek citizen among the dead "binds us even more to the fight to eradicate hatred and terrorism in Europe".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The **Second Nagorno-Karabakh War** was an armed conflict in 2020 that took place in the disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh and the surrounding occupied territories.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It was a major escalation of an unresolved conflict over the region, involving Azerbaijan, Armenia and the self-declared Armenian breakaway state of Artsakh.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The war lasted for 44 days and resulted in Azerbaijani victory, with the defeat igniting anti-government protests in Armenia.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Post-war skirmishes continued in the region, including substantial clashes in 2022.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Fighting began on the morning of 27 September, with an Azerbaijani offensive along the line of contact established in the aftermath of the First Nagorno-Karabakh War (1988–1994).
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Clashes were particularly intense in the less mountainous districts of southern Nagorno-Karabakh.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Turkey provided military support to Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The war was marked by the deployment of drones, sensors, long-range heavy artillery and missile strikes, as well as by state propaganda and the use of official social media accounts in online information warfare.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In particular, Azerbaijan's widespread use of drones was seen as crucial in determining the conflict's outcome.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Numerous countries and the United Nations strongly condemned the fighting and called on both sides to de-escalate tensions and resume meaningful negotiations.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Three ceasefires brokered by Russia, France, and the United States failed to stop the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Following the capture of Shusha, the second-largest city in Nagorno-Karabakh, a ceasefire agreement was signed, ending all hostilities in the area from 10 November 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The agreement resulted in a major shift regarding the control of the territories in Nagorno-Karabakh and the areas surrounding it.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Approximately 2,000 Russian soldiers were deployed as peacekeeping forces along the Lachin corridor connecting Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh, with a mandate of at least five years.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Following the end of the war, an unconfirmed number of Armenian prisoners of war were held captive in Azerbaijan, with reports of mistreatment and charges filed against them, leading to a case at the International Court of Justice.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The later 2023 Azerbaijani offensive in Nagorno-Karabakh would see the entirety of the disputed territory come under the control of Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The war has been referred to as the "Second Nagorno-Karabakh War", and has also been called the "44-Day War" in both Armenia and Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In Armenia and Artsakh, it has been called the "Second Artsakh War" (Armenian: Արցախյան երկրորդ պատերազմ, romanized: *Arts'akhyan yerkrord paterazm*), "Patriotic War" and the "Fight for Survival" (Armenian: Գոյամարտ, romanized: *Goyamart*).
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In Azerbaijan, it has been called the "Second Karabakh War" (Azerbaijani: *İkinci Qarabağ müharibəsi*) and "Patriotic War".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Azerbaijani government referred to it as an "operation for peace enforcement" and "counter-offensive operation".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It later announced it had initiated military operations under the code-name "Operation Iron Fist" (Azerbaijani: *Dəmir Yumruq əməliyyatı*).
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The territorial ownership of Nagorno-Karabakh is fiercely contested between Armenians and Azerbaijanis.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The current conflict has its roots in events following World War I and today the region is *de jure* part of Azerbaijan, although large parts were *de facto* held by the internationally unrecognised Republic of Artsakh, which is supported by Armenia.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] During the Soviet era, the predominantly Armenian-populated region was governed as an autonomous oblast within the Azerbaijan SSR.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] As the Soviet Union began to disintegrate during the late 1980s the question of Nagorno-Karabakh's status re-emerged, and on 20 February 1988 the parliament of the Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Oblast passed a resolution requesting transfer of the oblast from the Azerbaijan SSR to the Armenian SSR.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijan rejected the request several times, and ethnic violence began shortly thereafter with a series of pogroms between 1988 and 1990 against Armenians in Sumgait, Ganja and Baku, and against Azerbaijanis in Gugark and Stepanakert.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Following the revocation of Nagorno-Karabakh's autonomous status, an independence referendum was held in the region on 10 December 1991.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The referendum was boycotted by the Azerbaijani population, which then constituted around 22.8% of the region's population; 99.8% of participants voted in favour.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In early 1992, following the Soviet Union's collapse, the region descended into outright war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The First Nagorno-Karabakh War resulted in the displacement of approximately 725,000 Azerbaijanis and 300,000–500,000 Armenians from both Azerbaijan and Armenia.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The terms of the Bishkek agreement produced a frozen conflict, and long-standing international mediation attempts to create a peace process were initiated by the OSCE Minsk Group in 1994, with the interrupted Madrid Principles being the most recent iteration prior to the 2020 war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] For three decades multiple violations of the ceasefire occurred, the most serious being the four-day 2016 Nagorno-Karabakh conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Surveys indicated that the inhabitants of Nagorno-Karabakh did not want to be part of Azerbaijan and in 2020 the Armenian prime minister Nikol Pashinyan announced plans to make Shusha, a city of historical and cultural significance to both Armenians and Azerbaijanis, Artsakh's new capital.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In August of the same year the government of Artsakh moved the country's parliament to Shusha, escalating tensions between Armenia and Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Further skirmishes occurred on the border between the two countries in July 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Thousands of Azerbaijanis rallied for war against Armenia in response, and Turkey voiced its firm support for Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 29 July 2020, Azerbaijan conducted a series of military exercises that lasted from 29 July to 10 August 2020, followed by further exercises in early September with the involvement of Turkey.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Prior to the resumption of hostilities, allegations emerged that Turkey had facilitated the transfer of hundreds of Syrian National Army members from the Hamza Division to Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Baku denied the involvement of foreign fighters.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The conflict was characterised by the widespread use of combat drones, particularly by Azerbaijan, as well as heavy artillery barrages, rocket attacks and trench warfare.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Throughout the campaign, Azerbaijan relied heavily on drone strikes against Armenian/Artsakh forces, inflicting heavy losses upon Armenian tanks, artillery, air defence systems and military personnel, although some Azerbaijani drones were shot down.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It also featured the deployment of cluster munitions, which are banned by the majority of the international community but not by Armenia or Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Both Armenia and Azerbaijan used cluster munitions against civilian areas outside of the conflict zone.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] A series of missile attacks on Ganja, Azerbaijan inflicted mass civilian casualties, as did artillery strikes on Stepanakert, Artsakh's capital.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Much of Stepanakert's population fled during the course of the fighting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The conflict was accompanied by coordinated attempts to spread misleading content and disinformation via social media and the internet.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The conflict began with an Azerbaijani ground offensive that included armoured formations, supported by artillery and drones, including loitering munitions.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Armenian and Artsakh troops were forced back from their first line of defence in Artsakh's southeast and northern regions, but inflicted significant losses on Azerbaijani armoured formations with anti-tank guided missiles and artillery, destroying dozens of vehicles.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijan made heavy use of drones in strikes against Armenian air defences, taking out 13 short-range surface-to-air missile systems.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijani forces used drones to systematically isolate and destroy Armenian/Artsakh positions.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Reconnaissance drones would locate a military position on the front lines and the placement of reserve forces, after which the position would be shelled along with roads and bridges that could potentially be used by the reserves to reach the position.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] After the Armenian/Artsakh position had been extensively shelled and cut off from reinforcement, the Azerbaijanis would move in superior forces to overwhelm it.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] This tactic was repeatedly used to gradually overrun Armenian and Artsakh positions.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijani troops managed to make limited gains in the south in the first three days of the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] For the next three days, both sides largely exchanged fire from fixed positions.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In the north, Armenian/Artsakh forces counterattacked, managing to retake some ground.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Their largest counterattack took place on the fourth day, but incurred heavy losses when their armour and artillery units were exposed to Azerbaijani attack drones, loitering munitions, and reconnaissance drones spotting for Azerbaijani artillery as they manoeuvred in the open.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijan targeted infrastructure throughout Artsakh starting on the first day of the war, including the use of rocket artillery and cluster munitions against Stepanakert, the capital of Artsakh, and a missile strike against a bridge in the Lachin Corridor linking Armenia with Artsakh.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On the 6th day of the war, Armenia/Artsakh targeted Ganja for the first of four times with ballistic missiles, nominally targeting the military portion of Ganja International Airport but instead hitting residential areas.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On the morning of the seventh day, Azerbaijan launched a major offensive.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Azerbaijani Army's First, Second, and Third Army Corps, reinforced by reservists from the Fourth Army Corps, began an advance in the north, making some territorial gains, but the Azerbaijani advance stalled.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Most of the fighting subsequently shifted to the south, in terrain that is relatively flat and underpopulated as compared to the mountainous north.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijani forces launched offensives toward Jabrayil and Füzuli, managing to break through the multi-layered Armenian/Artsakh defensive lines and recapture a stretch of territory held by Armenian troops as a buffer zone, but the fighting subsequently stalled.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] After the shelling of Martuni, Artsakh authorities began mobilising civilians.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Just before 04:00 (00:00 UTC) on 10 October 2020, Russia reported that both Armenia and Azerbaijan had agreed on a humanitarian ceasefire after ten hours of talks in Moscow (the Moscow Statement) and announced that both would enter "substantive" talks.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] After the declared ceasefire, the President of Artsakh admitted Azerbaijan had been able to achieve some success, moving the front deep into Artsakh territory; the Armenian Prime Minister announced that Armenian forces had conducted a "partial retreat".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The ceasefire quickly broke down and the Azerbaijani advance continued.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Within days Azerbaijan announced the capture of dozens of villages on the southern front.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] A second ceasefire attempt midnight 17 October 2020 was also ignored.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijan announced the capture of Jabrayil on 9 October 2020 and Füzuli on 17 October 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijani troops also captured the Khoda Afarin Dam and Khodaafarin Bridges.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijan announced that the border area with Iran was fully secured with the capture of Agbend on 22 October 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijani forces then turned northwest, advancing towards the Lachin corridor, the sole highway between Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh, putting it within artillery range.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] According to Artsakh, a counterattack repelled forward elements of the Azerbaijani force and pushed them back.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Armenian/Artsakh resistance had managed to halt the Azerbaijani advance to within 25 kilometres of the Lachin corridor by 26 October 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Artsakh troops who had retreated into the mountains and forests began launching small-unit attacks against exposed Azerbaijani infantry and armour, and Armenian forces launched a counteroffensive near the far southwestern border between Armenia and Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 26 October 2020, a US-brokered ceasefire came into effect, but fighting resumed within minutes.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Three days later, the Artsakh authorities stated that the Azerbaijani forces were 5 km (3.1 mi) from Shusha.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 8 November 2020, Azerbaijani forces seized Shusha, the second-largest city in Artsakh before the war, located 15 kilometres from Stepanakert, the republic's capital.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Although the amount of territory contested was relatively restricted, the conflict impacted the wider region, in part due to the type of munitions deployed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Shells and rockets landed in East Azerbaijan Province, Iran, although no damage was reported, and Iran reported that several unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) had been downed or had crashed within its territory.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Georgia stated that two UAVs had crashed in its Kakheti Province.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The President of Artsakh, Arayik Harutyunyan, also agreed to end the hostilities.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Under the terms of the deal, both belligerent parties were to exchange prisoners of war and the bodies of the fallen.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Additionally, Armenia undertook to "guarantee safety" of transport communication between Azerbaijan's Nakhchivan exclave and mainland Azerbaijan in both directions, while Russia's border troops (under the Federal Security Service) were to "exercise control over the transport communication".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 15 December 2020, after several weeks of cease fire, the sides finally exchanged prisoners of war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] 44 Armenian and 12 Azeri prisoners were exchanged.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It is unclear whether more prisoners remain in captivity on either side.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] At the time of the ceasefire, Azerbaijan had retaken most of the area south of the Lachin corridor.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It had also captured one-third of Nagorno-Karabakh, mostly in the south.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Under the terms of the ceasefire, Azerbaijan regained control over much of its territory that had been lost to Armenia in the earlier war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In total, Azerbaijan regained control of 72% of the disputed territory, including the territory captured in Nagorno-Karabakh.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It was reported that Azerbaijan regained control of 5 cities, 4 towns, 286 villages.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Since the beginning of the conflict, both Armenia and Azerbaijan declared martial law, limiting the freedom of speech.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Meanwhile, a new law came into effect since October 2020 in Armenia, which prohibits negative coverage of the situation at the front.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Restrictions have been reported on the work of international journalists in Azerbaijan, with no corresponding restrictions reported in Nagorno-Karabakh.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 28 September 2020, Armenia banned men aged over 18 listed in the mobilisation reserve from leaving the country.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The next day, it postponed the trial of former President Robert Kocharyan and other former officials charged in the 2008 post-election unrest case, owing to one of the defendants, the former Defence Minister of Armenia, Seyran Ohanyan, going to Artsakh during the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 1 October 2020, the Armenian National Security Service (NSS) stated that it had arrested and charged a former high-ranking Armenian military official with treason on suspicion of spying for Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Three days later, the NSS stated that it had arrested several foreign citizens on suspicion of spying.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Protesting Israeli arms sales to Azerbaijan, Armenia recalled its ambassador to Israel.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 8 October 2020, the Armenian President, Armen Sarkissian, dismissed the director of the NSS.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Subsequently, the Armenian government toughened the martial law and prohibited criticising state bodies and "propaganda aimed at disruption of the defense capacity of the country".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On the same day, the Armenian MoD cancelled *a Novaya Gazeta* correspondent's journalistic accreditation, officially for entering Nagorno-Karabakh without accreditation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 9 October 2020, Armenia tightened its security legislation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 21 October 2020, the Armenian Cabinet of Ministers temporarily banned the import of Turkish goods, the decision will come into force on 31 December 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The following day, the Armenian parliament passed a law to write off the debts of the Armenian servicemen wounded during the clashes and the debts of the families of those killed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 27 October 2020, the Armenian president Armen Sarkissian dismissed the head of the counterintelligence department of the National Security Service, Major General Hovhannes Karumyan and the chief of staff of the border troops of the National Security Service Gagik Tevosyan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 8 November 2020, Sarkissian yet again dismissed the interim head of the National Security Service.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] As of 8 November 2020, one Armenian activist was fined by the police for his anti-war post.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 27 September 2020, Azerbaijani authorities restricted internet access shortly after the clashes began, stating it was "in order to prevent large-scale Armenian provocations." The government made a noticeable push to use Twitter, which was the only unblocked platform in the country.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Despite the restrictions, some Azerbaijanis still used VPNs to bypass them.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The National Assembly of Azerbaijan declared a curfew in Baku, Ganja, Goygol, Yevlakh and a number of districts from midnight on 28 September 2020, under the Interior Minister, Vilayet Eyvazov.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Azerbaijan Airlines announced that all airports in Azerbaijan would be closed to regular passenger flights until 30 September 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Military Prosecutor's Offices of Fuzuli, Tartar, Karabakh and Ganja began criminal investigations of war and other crimes.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Also on 28 September 2020, the President of Azerbaijan, Ilham Aliyev, issued a decree authorising a partial mobilisation in Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 8 October 2020, Azerbaijan recalled its ambassador to Greece for consultations, following allegations of Armenians from Greece arriving in Nagorno-Karabakh to fight against Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Three days later, the Azerbaijani State Security Service (SSS) warned against a potential Armenian-backed terror attack.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 17 October 2020, the Azerbaijani MoFA stated that member of the Russian State Duma from the ruling United Russia, Vitaly Milonov, was declared *persona non grata* in Azerbaijan for visiting Nagorno-Karabakh without permission from the Azerbaijani government.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 24 October 2020, by recommendation of the Central Bank of Azerbaijan, the member banks of the Azerbaijani Banks' Association unanimously adopted a decision to write off the debts of the military servicemen and civilians who died during the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 29 October 2020, the President of Azerbaijan, Ilham Aliyev, issued a decree on the formation of temporary commandant's offices in the areas that the Azerbaijani forces seized control of during the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] According to the decree, the commandants will be appointed by the Ministry of Internal Affairs, but they will have to coordinate with other executive bodies of the government, including Ministry of Defense, the State Border Service, the State Security Service, and ANAMA.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Over the course of the war several Azerbaijani activists were brought in for questioning by the State Security Service, due to their anti-war activism.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 12 December, a decree by President Aliyev lifted the curfew that had been imposed in September.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Casualties were high, officially in the low thousands.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] According to official figures released by the belligerents, Armenia lost 3,825 troops killed and 187 missing, while Azerbaijan lost 2,906 troops killed, with six missing in action.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] During the conflict, it was noted that the sides downplayed the number of their own casualties and exaggerated the numbers of enemy casualties and injuries.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Armenian authorities stated that 85 Armenian civilians were killed during the war, while another 21 were missing.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] According to Azerbaijani sources, the Armenian military has targeted densely populated areas containing civilian structures.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] As of 9 November 2020, the Prosecutor General's Office of the Republic of Azerbaijan stated that during the war, as a result of reported shelling by Armenian artillery and rocketing, 100 people had been killed, while 416 people had been wounded.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Also, during the post-war clashes, the Azerbaijani authorities stated that an Azercell employee was seriously injured during the installation of communication facilities and transmission equipment near Hadrut.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] As of 23 October 2020, the Armenian authorities has stated that the conflict had displaced more than half of Nagorno-Karabakh's population or approximately 90,000 people.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The International Rescue Committee has also claimed that more than half of the population of Nagorno-Karabakh has been displaced by the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] As of 2 November 2020, the Azerbaijani authorities has stated that the conflict had displaced approximately 40,000 people in Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 1 October 2020, two French journalists from *Le Monde* covering the clashes in Khojavend were injured by Azerbaijani shellfire.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] A week later, three Russian journalists reporting in Shusha were seriously injured by an Azerbaijani attack.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 19 October 2020, according to Azerbaijani sources, an Azerbaijani AzTV journalist received shrapnel wounds from Armenian shellfire in Aghdam District.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] by the Azerbaijani forces, displayed on 10 December during the victory parade.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Armenian authorities reported the deaths of 3,825 servicemen during the war, while the Azerbaijani authorities stated that more than 5,000 Armenian servicemen were killed, and several times more were wounded as of 28 October 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] After the war, the former director of the Armenian National Security Service, Artur Vanetsyan, had also stated that some 5,000 Armenians were killed during the war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Also, the Armenian authorities had stated that about 60 Armenian servicemen were captured by Azerbaijan as prisoners of war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The former Head of the Military Control Service of the Armenian MoD, Movses Hakobyan, stated that already on the fifth day of war there were 1,500 deserters from Armenian armed forces, who were kept in Karabakh and not allowed to return to Armenia in order to prevent panic.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The press secretary of Armenian prime minister called the accusations absurd and asked the law enforcement agencies to deal with them.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Former military commissar of Armenia major-general Levon Stepanyan stated that the number of deserters in Armenian army was over 10,000, and it is not possible to prosecute such a large number of military personnel.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] During the post-war clashes, the Armenian government stated that 60 servicemen went missing, including several dozen that were captured. and On 27 October 2020, Artsakh authorities stated that its defence minister Jalal Harutyunyan was wounded in action.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] However, unofficial Azerbaijani military sources alleged that he was killed and released footage apparently showing the assassination from a drone camera.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] During the conflict, the government of Azerbaijan did not reveal the number of its military casualties.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 11 January, Azerbaijan stated that 2,853 of its soldiers had been killed during the war, while another 50 went missing.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Also, Azerbaijani authorities stated that 11 more Azerbaijani servicemen were killed during the post-war clashes or landmine explosions.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 23 October 2020, President of Azerbaijan, Ilham Aliyev, confirmed that Shukur Hamidov who was made National Hero of Azerbaijan in 2016, was killed during the operations in Qubadli District.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] This was the first military casualty officially confirmed by the government.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] However, Armenian and Artsakh authorities have claimed 7,630 Azerbaijani soldiers and Syrian mercenaries were killed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Syrian Observatory for Human Rights documented the death of at least 541 Syrian fighters or mercenaries fighting for Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 14 November 2020, the Observatory reported the death of a commander of the Syrian National Army's Hamza Division.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Civilian areas, including major cities, have been hit, including Azerbaijan's second-largest city, Ganja, and the region's capital, Stepanakert, with many buildings and homes destroyed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Ghazanchetsots Cathedral has also been damaged.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Several outlets reported increased cases of COVID-19 in Nagorno-Karabakh, particularly the city of Stepanakert, where the population was forced to live in overcrowded bunkers, due to Azerbaijan artillery and drone strikes conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] There were also reported difficulties in testing and contact tracing during the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Ghazanchetsots Cathedral in Shusha became damaged as a result of shelling.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 19 October 2020, a strong fire broke out in a cotton plant in Azad Qaraqoyunlu, Tartar District, as a result of the Armenian artillery shelling, with several large hangars of the plant becoming completely burned down.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] An Armenian-backed Nagorno-Karabakh human rights ombudsman report noted 5,800 private properties and 520 private vehicles destroyed, with damage to 960 items of civilian infrastructure, and industrial and public and objects.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 16 November 2020, the Prosecutor General's Office of the Republic of Azerbaijan reported 3,410 private houses, 512 civilian facilities, and 120 multi-storey residential buildings being damaged throughout the war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] As of 16 October 2020, the Azerbaijani President stated that the Armenian losses were at US$2 billion.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In turn an Azerbaijani helicopter was stated to have been damaged, but its crew had apparently returned it to Azerbaijani-controlled territory without casualties.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Later it was reported that on 12 October 2020, Azerbaijan had destroyed one Tochka-U missile launcher.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 14 October 2020, Azerbaijan stated it had further destroyed five T-72 tanks, three BM-21 Grad rocket launchers, one 9K33 Osa missile system, one BMP-2 vehicle, one KS-19 air defence gun, two D-30 howitzers and several Armenian army automobiles.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On the same day, Azerbaijan announced the destruction of three R-17 Elbrus tactical ballistic missile launchers that had been targeting Ganja and Mingachevir.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] BBC reporters confirmed the destruction of at least one tactical ballistic missile launcher in the vicinity of Vardenis, close to the border with Azerbaijan, and posted photo evidence in support of this information.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Later American journalist Josh Friedman posted a high quality video of a destroyed Armenian ballistic missile launcher.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Armenian and Artsakh authorities initially reported the downing of four Azerbaijani helicopters and the destruction of ten tanks and IFVs, as well as 15 drones.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Later the numbers were revised to 36 tanks and armoured personnel vehicles destroyed, two armoured combat engineering vehicles destroyed and four helicopters and 27 unmanned aerial vehicles downed all within the first day of hostilities.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] They released footage showing the destruction or damage of five Azerbaijani tanks.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Over the course of 2 October, the Artsakh Defence Army said they had destroyed 39 Azerbaijani military vehicles, including a T-90 tank; four SU-25 fighter-bombers; three Mi-24 attack helicopters; and 17 UAVs.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Oryx only counts destroyed vehicles and equipment of which photo or videographic evidence is available, and therefore, the actual number of equipment destroyed is higher.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] UN Secretary-General António Guterres stated that "indiscriminate attacks on populated areas anywhere, including in Stepanakert, Ganja and other localities in and around the immediate Nagorno-Karabakh zone of conflict, were totally unacceptable".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Shortly after the news about the signing the ceasefire agreement broke in the early hours of 10 November violent protests erupted in Armenia against Nikol Pashinyan, claiming he was a "traitor" for having accepted the peace deal.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Protesters also seized the parliament building by breaking a metal door, and pulled the President of the National Assembly of Armenia Ararat Mirzoyan from a car and beat him.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] After the ceasefire agreement was signed, President Armen Sarksyan held a meeting with Karekin II, where they both made a call to declare 22 November as the Day of Remembrance of the Heroes who fell for the Defense of the Motherland in the Artsakh Liberation War.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 16 November, he declared that snap parliamentary elections and Pashinyan's resignation were inevitable, proposing that a process be overseen and managed by an interim "National Accord Government".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 10 December, the Armenian media reported that an Azerbaijani citizen was detained at night near Berdavan in Tavush Province.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It was reported that an Azerbaijani civilian was observed in Berdavan between 4:00 and 5:00 in the morning.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The executive head of Berdavan, Smbat Mugdesyan, said that the NSS had taken him away and that he did not know other details.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] According to the Armenian media, a criminal case was opened against the detained citizen on suspicion of illegally crossing to the Armenian state border.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The name of the detained Azerbaijani was not disclosed.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] According to the *BBC Azerbaijani Service*, Azerbaijan's Internal Affairs, Foreign Affairs and Defence Ministries said they had no information about the incident.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 12 December, Azerbaijani trucks, accompanied by the International Committee of the Red Cross and Russian peacekeepers, entered David Bek in Syunik Province of Armenia to pick up the bodies of fallen soldiers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Armenian officials refuted the media reports of Azerbaijani vehicles entering Goris.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 16 December, the family members of the missing Armenian soldiers gathered in front of the Armenian Ministry of Defence building, demanding information about their loved ones.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] They were not allowed into the building and Armenian military representatives did not give a response.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] A scuffle ensued, during which the family members of the missing Armenian soldiers broke through to the building.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The peace agreement and the end of the war was seen as a victory and was widely celebrated in Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 10 November 2020, crowds waved flags in Baku after the peace deal was announced.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On that day, President of Azerbaijan Ilham Aliyev gave a speech in which he mockingly said *Nə oldu Paşinyan?* ("What happened Pashinyan?"), which became an Internet meme in Azerbaijan and Turkey.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] About a week later, at a plenary session of the Azerbaijani National Assembly, a draft law on amendments to the law "On the establishment of orders and medals of the Republic of Azerbaijan" was submitted for discussion.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Seventeen new orders and medals were established on the same day in the first reading in accordance with the bill "On the establishment of orders and medals of the Republic of Azerbaijan".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In mid-November, Aliyev and Azerbaijan's First Vice-president, Mehriban Aliyeva, visited Fuzuli and Jabrayil Districts, both of which were ghost towns in ruins after the Armenian forces occupied it in 1993.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Aliyev ordered the State Agency of Azerbaijan Automobile Roads to construct a new highway, starting from Alxanlı, which will connect Fuzuli to Shusha.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In Jabrayil, Aliyev stated that a "new master plan" will be drawn up to rebuild the city.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] 27 September and 10 November were declared Memorial Day and Victory Day respectively, although the latter's date was changed to 8 November as it overlapped with Mustafa Kemal Atatürk's Memorial Day in Turkey.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] It was also announced that the new station in the Baku Metro will be named 8 November at the suggestion of Aliyev.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On the same day, President Aliyev signed a decree on the establishment of the YASHAT Foundation to support the families of those wounded and killed during the war, and general control over the management of the foundation was transferred to the ASAN service.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 2 December, the Association of Banks of Azerbaijan announced that the bank debts of servicemen and civilians killed during the war in Azerbaijan would be completely written off.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 4 December, at 12:00 (GMT+4) local time, a moment of silence was held in Azerbaijan to commemorate the fallen soldiers of the war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Flags were lowered across the country, and traffic halted, while ships moored in the Bay of Baku, as well as cars honked their horns.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] On 9 December, President Aliyev awarded 83 servicemen with the title of Hero of the Patriotic War, 204 servicemen with Karabakh Order, and 33 servicemen with Zafar Order.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Turkish President Erdoğan attended the military parade as part of a state visit to Baku.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In April 2021, Azerbaijan opened a Military Trophy Park featuring items from the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] The Armenian population of the territories ceded to Azerbaijan was forced to flee to Armenia, sometimes destroying their houses and livestock to keep them out of Azerbaijani hands.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In 2020, Canada suspended arms exports to Turkey due to accusations of the use of Canadian technology in the conflict, in violation of end-use assurances Turkey had given to Canada.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Turkey criticised the Canadian decision.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] In 2021, Canada prohibited arms exports to Turkey after an investigation verified the accusations.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p01] Turkey protested that the embargo will harm bilateral relations and NATO alliance solidarity.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] While Armenians and Azerbaijanis lived side by side under Soviet rule, the collapse of the Soviet Union contributed to racialisation and fierce nationalism, causing both Armenians and Azerbaijanis to stereotype each other, shaping rhetoric on both sides.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The suspected immediate goal of the Azerbaijani offensive was to capture the districts of Fuzuli and Jabrayil in southern Nagorno-Karabakh, where the terrain is less mountainous and more favourable for offensive operations.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Political scientist Arkady Dubnov of the Carnegie Moscow Center believed that Azerbaijan had launched the offensive to improve Azerbaijan's position in a suitable season for hostilities in the terrain.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The geostrategic interests of Russia and Turkey in the region were widely commented upon during the war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Both were described as benefiting from the ceasefire agreement, with *The Economist* stating that for Russia, China and Turkey, "all sides stand to benefit economically".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan and Turkey are bound by ethnic, cultural and historic ties, and both countries refer to their relationship as being one between "two states, one nation".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Turkey (then the Ottoman Empire) helped Azerbaijan, previously part of the Russian Empire gain its independence in 1918, and became the first country to recognise Azerbaijan's independence from the Soviet Union in 1991.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Turkey has also been the guarantor of the Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic, an exclave of Azerbaijan, since 1921.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Other commentators have seen Turkey's support for Azerbaijan as part of an activist foreign policy, linking it with neo-Ottoman policies in Syria, Iraq, and the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Turkey's highly visible role in the conflict was described by Armenians as a continuation of the Armenian genocide, the mass murder and expulsion of 1.5 million Armenians by the Ottoman government, particularly given Turkey's continued denial of the genocide.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Turkey provided military support to Azerbaijan, including military experts and Syrian mercenaries.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The transport communications stipulated by the ceasefire agreement, linking Nakhchivan and the main part of Azerbaijan through Armenia, would provide Turkey with trade access to Central Asia and China's Belt and Road Initiative.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Russia had sought to maintain good relations with Azerbaijan and had sold weapons to both parties.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Even prior to the war, Russia had possessed a military base in Armenia as part of a military alliance with Armenia, and thus was obligated by treaty to defend Armenia in the case of a war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Like in Syria and in Libya's ongoing civil war, Russia and NATO-member Turkey therefore had opposing interests.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Turkey appeared to use the conflict to attempt to leverage its influence in the South Caucasus along its eastern border, using both military and diplomatic resources to extend its sphere of influence in the Middle East, and to marginalise the influence of Russia, another regional power.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Russia had historically pursued a policy of maintaining neutrality in the conflict, and Armenia never formally requested aid.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] According to the director of the Russia studies program at the CNA, at the beginning of the war Russia was judged to be unlikely to intervene militarily unless Armenia incurred drastic losses.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The Russian MoFA also released a statement, saying that Russia will provide Armenia with "all the necessary assistance" if the war continued on the territories of Armenia, as both countries are part of the Collective Security Treaty Organization.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Nonetheless, when the Azerbaijani forces reportedly struck the Armenian territories on 14 October 2020, Russia did not directly interfere in the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The relative success of Azerbaijan in meeting its strategic goals to gain control over Nagorno-Karabakh via the use of military force may have influenced the Russian decision to invade Ukraine in 2022.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan's oil wealth allowed a consistently higher military budget than Armenia, and it purchased advanced weapons systems from Israel, Russia and Turkey.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Despite the similar size of both militaries, Azerbaijan possessed superior tanks, armoured personnel carriers and infantry fighting vehicles, and had also amassed a fleet of Turkish and Israeli drones.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Armenia built its own drones, but these were greatly inferior to the Turkish and Israeli drones owned by Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan had a quantitative advantage in artillery systems, particularly self-propelled guns and long-range multiple rocket launchers, while Armenia had a minor advantage in tactical ballistic missiles.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Because of the air defence systems of both sides, there was little use of manned aviation during the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] In the opinion of a Forbes magazine contributor, Azerbaijan managed to inflict a devastating and decisive defeat through adept usage of sophisticated military hardware which avoided bogging down in a costly war of attrition.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] According to Forbes, Azerbaijan had prepared itself for tomorrow's war rather than a repeat of yesterday's war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] In the opinion voiced by Russian military expert Vladimir Yevseev after the war, for unclear reasons Armenia appeared not to have executed the mobilisation it had announced and hardly any mobilised personnel were deployed to the conflict area.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan made devastating use of drones and sensors, demonstrating what *The Economist* described as a "new, more affordable type of air power".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijani drones, notably the Turkish-made Bayraktar TB2, carried out precise strikes as well as reconnaissance, relaying the coordinates of targets to Azerbaijani artillery.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Commentators noted how drones enabled small countries to conduct effective air campaigns, potentially making low-level conflicts much more deadly.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Close air support was provided by specialised suicide drones such as the Israeli-made IAI Harop loitering munition, rendering tanks vulnerable and suggesting the need for changes to armoured warfare doctrine.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Another suicide drone, the Turkish-made STM Kargu, was also reportedly used by Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Concerns were raised about the security of the petroleum industry in Azerbaijan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan claimed that Armenia targeted, or tried to target, the Baku–Tbilisi–Ceyhan pipeline, which accounted for around 80% of country's oil exports, and the Baku–Novorossiysk pipeline.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Both sides engaged in extensive propaganda campaigns through official mainstream and social media accounts magnified online, including in Russian media.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Video from drones recording their kills was used in highly effective Azerbaijani propaganda.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] In Baku, digital billboards broadcast high-resolution footage of missiles striking Armenian soldiers, tanks, and materiel.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan's President Ilham Aliyev told Turkish television that Azerbaijani-operated drones had reduced the number of Azerbaijan's casualties, stating, "These drones show Turkey's strength" and "empower" Azerbaijanis.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Hackers from Armenia and Azerbaijan as well as their allied countries have waged cyberwarfare, with Azerbaijani hackers targeting Armenian websites and posting Aliyev's statements, and Greek hackers targeting Azerbaijani governmental websites.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] There have been coordinated messages posted from both sides.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Misinformation and videos of older events and other conflicts have been shared as new.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] New social media accounts posting about Armenia and Azerbaijan have spiked, with many from authentic users, but many inauthentic also.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] According to the EU Parliament, Azerbaijani information operations also specifically aimed at harassing Armenia social media users.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 27 September 2020, the Prime Minister of Armenia, Nikol Pashinyan, accused the Azerbaijani authorities of a large-scale provocation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The next day, Armenia's Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MoFA) issued a statement, noting that the "people of Artsakh were at war with the Turkish–Azerbaijani alliance".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The same day, the Armenian ambassador to Russia, Vardan Toganyan, did not rule out that Armenia may turn to Russia for fresh arms supplies.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 29 September 2020, Prime Minister Pashinyan stated that Azerbaijan, with military support from Turkey, was expanding the theatre into Armenian territory.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 30 September 2020, Pashinyan stated that Armenia was considering officially recognising the Republic of Artsakh as an independent territory.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The same day, the Armenian MoFA stated that the Turkish Air Force had carried out provocative flights along the front between the forces of the Republic of Artsakh and Azerbaijan, including providing air support to the Azerbaijani army.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 1 October 2020, the President of Artsakh, Arayik Harutyunyan, stated that Armenians needed to prepare for a long-term war.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Two days later, the Nagorno-Karabakh (Artsakh) Foreign Ministry called on the international community to recognise the independence of the Republic of Artsakh in order to restore regional peace and security.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 6 October 2020, the Armenian prime minister, Nikol Pashinyan, stated that the Armenian side was prepared to make concessions, if Azerbaijan was ready to reciprocate.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 9 October 2020, Armen Sarkissian demanded that international powers, particularly, the United States, Russia and NATO, do more to stop Turkey's involvement in the war and warned that Ankara is creating "another Syria in the Caucasus".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Pashinyan said that "to fight for the rights of our people means, first of all, to take up arms and commit to the protection of the rights of the homeland".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 12 November 2020, Pashinyan addressed his nation, saying that "Armenia and the Armenian people are living extremely difficult days.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] There is sorrow in the hearts of all of us, tears in the eyes of all of us, pain in the souls of all of us".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The prime minister pointed out that the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Armenia reported that the war "must be stopped immediately".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] And the President of Artsakh warned that if the hostilities do not stop, Stepanakert could be lost in days.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Pashinyan also stated that the Karabakh issue was not resolved and is not resolved and that the international recognition of the Artsakh Republic is becoming an absolute priority.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] According to the Azerbaijani Ministry of Defence, the Armenian military violated the ceasefire 48 times along the line of contact on 26 September 2020, the day before the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan stated that the Armenian side attacked first, prompting an Azerbaijani counter-offensive.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 27 September 2020, Azerbaijan accused Armenian forces of a "willful and deliberate" attack on the front line and of targeting civilian areas, alleging a "gross violation of international humanitarian law".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 28 September 2020, it stated that Armenia's actions had destroyed the peace negotiations through an act of aggression, alleged that a war had been launched against Azerbaijan, mobilised the people of Azerbaijan, and declared a Great Patriotic War.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] It then stated that the deployment of the Armenian military in Nagorno-Karabakh constituted a threat to regional peace and accused Armenia of propagandising, adding that the Azerbaijani military was operating according to international law.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The Azerbaijani authorities issued a statement accusing the Armenian military of purposefully targeting civilians, including women and children.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The Azerbaijani Minister of Foreign Affairs (MoFA) denied any reports of Turkish involvement, while admitting military-technical cooperation with Turkey and other countries.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] The Azerbaijani MoFA demanded that Armenia stop shelling civilians and called on international organisations to ensure Armenia followed international law.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Azerbaijan denied reports of mercenaries brought in from Turkey by Azerbaijan, and the First Vice-president of the Republic of Azerbaijan, Mehriban Aliyeva, stated that Azerbaijan had never laid claim to others' territory nor committed crimes against humanity.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 3 October 2020, Aliyev stated that Armenia needed to leave Azerbaijan's territory (in Nagorno-Karabakh) for the war to stop.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] He added that Azerbaijan would restore its cities and destroyed mosques and accused Armenia of distorting history.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Two days later, Aliyev's aide, Hikmat Hajiyev, said that Armenia had deployed cluster munitions against cities, however this had not been verified by other sources.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] He also accused Armenia of ethnic discrimination on account of the historical expulsion or self-exile of ethnic minority communities, highlighting its mono-ethnic population.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 10 October 2020, Azerbaijani Foreign Minister Jeyhun Bayramov stated that the truce signed on the same day was temporary.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Despite this, Aliyev stated that both parties were now attempting to determine a political resolution to the conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 21 October 2020, Aliyev stated that Azerbaijan did not rule out the introduction of international observers and peacekeepers in Nagorno-Karabakh, but will put forward some conditions when the time comes.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] He then added that Azerbaijan did not agree for a referendum in Nagorno-Karabakh, but didn't exclude the cultural autonomy of Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh, and reaffirmed that the Azerbaijan considers Armenians living in Nagorno-Karabakh as their citizens, promising security and rights.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] On 26 October 2020, Aliyev stated that the Azerbaijani government will inspect and record the destruction by Armenian forces in Armenian-occupied territories surrounding Nagorno-Karabakh during the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2020-nagorno-karabakh-conflict-p02] Because of the geography, history, and sensitivities of the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict, accusations, allegations, and statements have been made of involvement by third-party and international actors.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] On May 19, 2022, a mass shooting occurred in Chicago, Illinois, United States, in the city's Near North Side neighborhood, near Michigan Avenue.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Two people were killed, and eight others were injured.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The perpetrator, Jaylun Sanders, was taken into custody by Chicago police.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The shooting occurred at about 10:40 p.m.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] CDT (UTC−05:00), near a McDonald's establishment on the Near North Side neighborhood of Chicago.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The incident occurred a few blocks from the city's Magnificent Mile shopping district.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The shooting happened as a result of an altercation outside the McDonald's restaurant.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The cause of the altercation is not yet known; however it was described as "personal" by detectives.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The shooting was triggered when police officers, who were near the area noticed two groups engaging in a fight.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] They found 21 spent shell casings at the scene.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] After the shooting, the suspect fled and caused a chase between police officials to the Chicago station of the city's Red Line.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Amid the chase, a woman fell onto the tracks and was electrocuted at the State Street subway.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Passengers from this station were evacuated at around 11:30 p.m., an hour after the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Several of the victims were hospitalized at Northwestern Memorial Hospital.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] All wounded victims were reported under serious condition.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The shooting was significant because it happened a week after a shooting in downtown Chicago's Millennium Park where a teen was shot and killed and led the city to enforce a curfew for young people.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Three days after the shooting, 21-year-old Chicago native Jaylun Sanders was identified as the suspect.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The weapon used was a Glock 19 handgun that Sanders had purchased from a relative in Indiana.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The Glock was also outfitted with a device which allows fully automatic fire.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Two people were killed in the shooting, one of the victims being 30-year-old Antonio Wade.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Wade was one of the individuals involved in the altercation that led to the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The incident was recorded by several cell phones nearby the crime scene.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The second victim was 31-year-old Anthony Allen, who was shot in the back of the head and was hospitalized at John H.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] In the aftermath of the shooting, a suspect was arrested by police on May 20, 2022.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Another person was arrested for obstructing the officers from making an arrest at the scene.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] In response to the shooting, Mayor Lori Lightfoot called the shooting "an outrageous act of violence" and announced that the city would increase police presence near the area of the shooting.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] The *Chicago Tribune* reported that during the shooting, a fight had happened between a witness and police officials.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] In June, a juvenile was arrested in connection with the shooting after turning himself in to the police.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Lightfoot and Superintendent of the Chicago Police Department David Brown blamed the shooting on the parents of the suspects.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] In November 2024, Jaylun Sanders pleaded guilty to one count of first degree murder after more than 40 additional charges against him were dropped.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] His guilty plea came a year after a second man, Kameron Abram, was sentenced to seven years for weapons charges.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2022-near-north-side-shooting] Sanders was then sentenced to 43 years in prison.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The **2024 McDonald's *E. coli* outbreak** was an outbreak from September to October 2024 involving contaminated slivered onions on Quarter Pounders sold at McDonald's stores in 14 U.S. states.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] At least 104 people contracted *Escherichia coli*, and one person died.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) issued a public warning through its Coordinated Outbreak Response & Evaluation Network (CORE Network) about the E. coli outbreak on October 22.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] Their initial investigation noted 49 cases of E. coli throughout 10 U.S. states (Colorado, Kansas, Utah, Wyoming, and portions of Idaho, Iowa, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, New Mexico, and Oklahoma).
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) at the time did not confirm the origin, but the government agency suspected it was either slivered onions or beef patties.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] An update to the investigation was published on October 25 with 26 new cases, 12 new hospitalizations, and 3 new U.S. states (Oregon, Washington, and Utah).
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] On October 22, McDonald's stores in the affected states temporarily removed the Quarter Pounder from the menu or stopped serving it with the specific slivered onions and beef patties.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The Colorado Department of Agriculture (CDA) laboratories analyzed subsamples from all the lots of McDonald's brand fresh and frozen beef patties collected from various McDonald's locations in Colorado and found them to be negative for E. coli.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] A second update on the investigation was published on October 30, stating that epidemiologic and traceback information shows that fresh, slivered onions were the likely source of illness in this outbreak.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The Food Safety and Inspection Service (FSIS) performed a traceback of beef patties served on Quarter Pounders at McDonald's, and evidence did not point to ground beef as the likely source of contamination.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The Food and Drug Administration is looking into a Washington onion "grower of interest".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] A third update was published on November 13, adding 14 new cases, 7 new hospitalizations, and North Carolina to the affected states.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The FDA tested recalled onions in which one sample tested positive for non-O157:H7 Shiga toxin-producing *E. coli*.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The *E. coli* found was not the outbreak strain.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] A fourth and final update was published on December 3, with no additional cases.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] On October 25, Taylor Farms, the supplier of the slivered onions to the affected stores, initiated a voluntary recall on yellow onions.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] While there were growers of interest that supplied Taylor Farms, FDA has not been able to implicate the specific grower.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] On December 3, 2024, the CDC declared the outbreak was "over," and the FDA announced they had closed their investigation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] The outbreak prompted several lawsuits against both McDonald's and the onion supplier, Taylor Fresh Foods.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] On October 23, 2024, a man who fell ill after eating a sandwich at a McDonald's location in Greeley, Colorado, filed one of the first lawsuits related to the incident.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] Later that month, a man filed a proposed class action lawsuit in the U.S.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] District Court for the Northern District of Illinois against McDonald's, alleging that the fast-food chain failed to disclose the risk of E. coli contamination leading to the illnesses.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] In November 2024, a lawsuit seeking class action status was filed in the U.S.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/2024-mcdonald-s-e-coli-outbreak] District Court for the Northern District of California against Taylor Fresh Foods, alleging that the company failed to warn consumers of an E. coli risk.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] During the summer of 2020, rumors swirled that Michael Jordan intended on purchasing an ownership stake in Richard Petty Motorsports, who fielded the only black driver in the NASCAR Cup Series, Bubba Wallace.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Such claims were repeatedly denied by Jordan's management team.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On September 8, 2021, veteran motorsports executive Steve Lauletta was named team president after serving as the interim president since the team's foundation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On July 12, 2022, 23XI Racing announced that two-time NASCAR Xfinity Series champion Tyler Reddick signed with the team for the 2024 season.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On July 23, 2022, Hamlin announced that starting in 2023, 23XI would have its own pit crews instead of leasing them from Joe Gibbs Racing.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] In May, 2024, 23XI opened its doors to their brand-new race shop and team headquarters, named "Airspeed", in Huntersville, North Carolina.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On October 2, 2024, it was announced that 23XI Racing, along with Front Row Motorsports, filed an antitrust lawsuit against NASCAR over the terms of the updated charter agreement, as well as anti-competitive practices committed by the France family.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On December 18, both teams were granted a motion of preliminary injunction, allowing them to race as chartered entries in 2025 while continuing their legal battle with NASCAR.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] The injunction also allowed the transfer of the two Stewart–Haas Racing charters to both teams.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Court of Appeals overturned the preliminary injunction ruling.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On August 25, NASCAR filed a legal notice of its agreement to issue one of the charters to a redacted entity.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On December 11, 2025, after eight days in court, the case was settled.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On September 21, 2020, Jordan and Denny Hamlin announced the formation of a Cup team to begin competition in 2021 with Jordan as majority owner, Hamlin as minority owner, and Wallace, who eleven days prior had announced his departure from Richard Petty Motorsports, as their first official driver.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] The team bought a guaranteed starting spot in every 2021 race by purchasing a charter from Germain Racing.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] The team's name, car number and manufacturer were not revealed at the time of the announcement.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Hamlin later said that the two had discussed owning a team but that it never came to fruition.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On October 22, the team announced its name, 23XI Racing, and would use the number 23 (Jordan's number during his basketball career).
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On October 30, the team revealed that they will run Toyotas with a technical alliance with Joe Gibbs Racing (whose No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 11 car is driven by Hamlin) and operate out of a shop owned (and formerly used) by Germain Racing.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On December 14, 23XI Racing announced that DoorDash, McDonald's, Columbia Sportswear, Dr Pepper, and Root, Inc. will be the sponsors of the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] It was also announced that several crew members of the former Germain operation would join the team as a pit crew.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On February 3, it was announced that former Germain driver Ty Dillon (who attempted to make the Daytona 500 with fellow Toyota team Gaunt Brothers Racing) would run the car in the 2021 Busch Clash, as Wallace was not eligible to run the clash.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace finished second in his Duel and finished seventeenth at the 2021 Daytona 500 after being involved in a last-lap crash.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] At the Daytona road course he had troubles all day and finished 26th.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace struggled out the gate until Phoenix, which was his first strong run of the season.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace was running top-fifteen for most of the day before working his way into the top-ten.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Following a caution and most of the field pitting, while Wallace stayed out, he restarted first.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] This move did not work out well for Wallace.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Due to him being on old tires and the rest of the field being on new tires, Wallace was quickly cycled out of the first position, dropped back, and wound up making contact with Cole Custer.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] At the 2021 GEICO 500 at Talladega, Wallace had a strong car the entire day.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace was running top-ten for a good portion of the day and ended up winning stage 2.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] This was Wallace's first career stage win.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] After an overtime restart, Wallace was cycled to the back of the pack and wound up finishing nineteenth.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] At Pocono, Wallace finished the first race in fourteenth, but finished the second race fifth, scoring the team's best finish and their first top-five.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He finished third at the 2021 Coke Zero Sugar 400 at Daytona, but he was officially scored with a second place finish after Chris Buescher was disqualified post-inspection.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On September 16, Bootie Barker was named crew chief for the remainder of the season after Wheeler was promoted to Director of Competition.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace scored his first career win at the rain-shortened 2021 YellaWood 500 at Talladega, becoming only the second Black driver after Wendell Scott to win a Cup race.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace finished the season 21st in points.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace began the 2022 season by finishing in second place at the 2022 Daytona 500.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On March 29, 2022, Barker was suspended for four races due to a tire and wheel loss during the 2022 Texas Grand Prix at COTA.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Dave Rogers was announced as Wallace's crew chief for Richmond, Martinsville, Bristol, and Talladega.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Later in the regular season, Wallace showed strong form, posting four consecutive top-10s at New Hampshire, Pocono, Indianapolis road course, and Michigan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] After failing to make the driver playoffs at Daytona, it was announced that Ty Gibbs would switch to the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 23 to allow Wallace to compete in the owners championship with the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] At the Texas playoff race, Gibbs veered into Ty Dillon on pit road, nearly sending Dillon towards a NASCAR official and a group of pit crew members; he was subsequently fined US$75,000 and the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] At Phoenix, Daniel Hemric substituted for Gibbs after the death of his father, Coy Gibbs.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace started the 2023 season with a twentieth place finish at the 2023 Daytona 500.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He improved his finishes enough to make the playoffs for the first time in his career.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace was eliminated from the Round of 12 at the conclusion of the Charlotte Roval race.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] During the 2024 season, Wallace was fined US$50,000 for intentionally door-slamming Alex Bowman during the cool-down lap after the Chicago street race.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Following the Martinsville playoff race, the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 23 was docked fifty owner and driver points and Wallace and the team were each fined US$100,000 for race manipulation, when Wallace faked a tire failure and slowed down to allow fellow Toyota driver Christopher Bell to pass him in an attempt to make the Championship 4.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] In addition, Barker was suspended for the Phoenix finale.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace started the 2025 season with a 29th place DNF at the 2025 Daytona 500.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He won at Indianapolis to break a 100-race winless streak and make the playoffs.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On November 20, 2024, 23XI announced that Riley Herbst would drive the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 35 was chosen by 23XI as an homage to Jordan's Minor League Baseball career.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Shortly after the Charlotte Roval race, the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 35 car was disqualified for failing post-race height inspection.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On May 30, 2026, it was announced that Corey Heim would be replacing Riley Herbst in the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On August 27, 2021, 23XI Racing announced that Kurt Busch will pilot the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 45 Toyota Camry in 2022 (With the number 45 being a reference to a jersey number Jordan wore during his baseball career and for 23 games during the 1994–95 NBA season.) His long time sponsor Monster Energy would follow him over.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Following the end of the 2021 season, 23XI purchased the former StarCom Racing's charter for US$13.5 million, making it the most expensive charter purchase since the implementation of the system in 2016.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Busch began his 2022 season with a nineteenth place finish at the 2022 Daytona 500.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Despite a promising start with top-five finishes at Phoenix and Atlanta, he suffered from poor finishes at COTA, Richmond, Bristol dirt, Dover, and Darlington.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] However, he rebounded with a win at Kansas.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] At the Pocono race, Busch was not medically cleared after a crash during qualifying, and subsequently missed the last five races of the regular season.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Xfinity Series driver Ty Gibbs substituted Busch for the next six races.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He finished sixteenth at Pocono and seventeenth at Indianapolis.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] A 10th-place finish at Michigan earned Gibbs his first top-10 finish.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] The following week at Richmond, Gibbs finished 36th, last due to an engine failure.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On August 25, Busch announced he withdrew his request for a playoff waiver.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Six days later, it was announced that Bubba Wallace would swap rides with Gibbs as the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 45 entry was still eligible for the owner's championship.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace finished ninth at Darlington to open the playoffs.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He scored his second career win at Kansas.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On October 16, Busch announced he would step away from full-time competition in 2023, with the possibility of running the season on a part-time basis.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] At Las Vegas, Kyle Larson charged aggressively past Kevin Harvick and Wallace, causing Wallace to scrape the outside wall.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace retaliated with a right rear hook on Larson, wrecking both cars down the frontstretch and severely damaging Christopher Bell's car in the process.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] During the caution, Wallace engaged in a shoving match with Larson.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Wallace was suspended for one race for the incident; John Hunter Nemechek was assigned to drive the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On October 15, 2022, 23XI Racing announced that it bought out the remainder of Tyler Reddick's contract from Richard Childress Racing to replace Kurt Busch in the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Reddick originally signed with 23XI for 2024, but Busch's concussion and subsequent retirement from full-time competition led to this move.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Reddick started the 2023 season with a 39th place DNF at the 2023 Daytona 500.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] A month later, he scored his first win of the season at COTA in triple overtime.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 45 team ten owner and driver points for unapproved ballasts during inspection prior to qualifying at Darlington.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] During the playoffs, Reddick won at Kansas to advance to the Round of 12.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Reddick started the 2024 season with a 29th place DNF at the 2024 Daytona 500.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He scored his first win of the season at Talladega by overtaking Brad Keselowski on the final stretch after Keselowski spun Michael McDowell and triggered a multi-car crash.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He scored his second win of the season at Michigan.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Following the Southern 500, Reddick clinched the regular season championship, beating Kyle Larson by just one point.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] During the playoffs, he locked himself into the Championship 4 by winning at Homestead.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Reddick started the 2025 season with a runner-up finish at the 2025 Daytona 500.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Despite having no wins, he stayed consistent enough to make the playoffs until he was eliminated after the Round of 12, finishing ninth in the points standings.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Reddick began the 2026 season by winning the 2026 Daytona 500, as well as Atlanta and COTA, becoming the first driver in Cup Series history to win the first three races in a season.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] In addition, Reddick won at Darlington and Kansas, becoming the first driver since Dale Earnhardt in 1987 to score five of the first nine races in a season.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On March 13, 2024, it was announced that Kobayashi would once again compete in a race for the team, this time at COTA.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 67 to celebrate the 50th anniversary of sponsor Mobil 1.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 50 for two more races during the season with different drivers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On May 10, 2024, 23XI Racing announced that Corey Heim would drive the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 50 Mobil 1 Toyota Camry at Nashville Superspeedway.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Heim finished 29th after crashing out in one of five overtimes.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On August 2, 2024, the team announced that Juan Pablo Montoya would make his NASCAR Cup Series return for 23XI at Watkins Glen on September 15.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] This would be the 3rd and final start for the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Montoya finished 32nd in his return to stock car racing.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On January 17, 2023, 23XI announced that Travis Pastrana would attempt to enter the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 67 Toyota Camry for the 2023 Daytona 500 with sponsorship coming from Black Rifle Coffee Company.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On February 14, Pastrana made the entry field by scoring the second fastest lap among the non-chartered teams.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] He suffered an accident in the qualifying duel and started in the back for the race.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] Pastrana ended up finishing eleventh in the race.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On June 7, it was announced that Kamui Kobayashi would make his Cup debut in the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 67 at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway Road Course, he would end up finishing 33rd in the race after getting caught up in several wrecks.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] On February 23, 2025, 23XI announced that Corey Heim signed a developmental deal that includes Cup races in the No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] 67, and Xfinity races in the Sam Hunt Racing No.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/23xi-racing] During the 2026 season, Heim scored his first career win at Naval Base Coronado.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Beginning in the late 1990s economic boom, an influx of thousands of African traders and business people, predominantly from West Africa, arrived in Guangzhou and created an African community in the middle of the southern Chinese metropolis.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Since 2014, the city's African population has significantly declined due to strict immigration enforcement by Chinese authorities and economic pressures in home countries, including depreciation of the Nigerian naira and Angolan kwanza.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Estimating the number of Africans in Guangzhou is difficult due to the highly mobile and transient nature of the community.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Most arrivals are short-term visitors engaged in trade, which can lead to inflated perceptions of the resident population.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] For instance, official figures recorded 430,000 arrivals and departures by African nationals at city checkpoints in the first nine months of 2014—figures that include repeat entries and do not reflect long-term residency.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In response to public concern during the 2014 Ebola outbreak, Guangzhou authorities stated that approximately 16,000 Africans, including North Africans, were living in the city.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Of these, only about 4,000 were considered long-term residents, defined as those staying over six months.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] A 2020 report estimated that 500,000 Africans were living in China, with around 100,000 in Guangzhou alone.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Scholar Adams Bodomo had earlier estimated over 500,000 Africans in China in 2012; however, his figure, based primarily on fieldwork, has been criticized as an overestimate due to the community's mobility.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Following 2014, population estimates began to decline.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] A 2014 article in *This Is Africa* cited stricter immigration enforcement and currency exchange issues as reasons for the decrease.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In 2016, CNN reported that thousands of African migrants had left Guangzhou in the preceding 18 months.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] By early 2017, official data indicated that the number of African residents had dropped to 10,344.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] According to the Public Security Bureau of Guangzhou, the figure declined further to 4,553 by 2020.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Researcher Roberto Castillo attributes this trend in part to the COVID-19 pandemic and stricter enforcement against overstayers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] By 2024, the African population in Guangzhou had reportedly rebounded to near pre-pandemic levels.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] This recovery is credited to the reopening of China's borders, renewed trade activity, and the easing of pandemic-era immigration controls.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Among African nationalities in Guangzhou, the largest groups are from Nigeria and Mali.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Nigerians, mainly of the Igbo ethnicity, constitute the largest group overall, while Malians represent a significant portion of long-term residents.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Other notable communities include migrants from the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ghana, and Senegal, with a few hundred individuals from each country registered with civic groups as of 2014.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Overstaying visas has been a significant factor influencing population estimates.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Many traders reported that the standard 30-day tourist visa was insufficient for conducting business, and the high cost of return flights made frequent travel impractical.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Anthropologists Gordon Mathews, Linessa Dan Lin, and Yang Yang found that Nigerians—particularly Igbos—were especially likely to overstay, linking the practice to social expectations and notions of "masculine pride," as well as family pressure to demonstrate success.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] There are two main areas where Africans live and do business in Guangzhou: Xiaobei and Guangyuanxi, both areas in the centrally located Yuexiu District.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The area of Xiaobei is near Xiaobei station and home to several streets catering to African and Middle Eastern residents.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Since the area was home to an existing Muslim population from Ningxia and Xinjiang, many African immigrants, around half of whom are Muslims, congregated around one area of town primarily because of the convenience in finding halal food.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Owing to the neighborhood's history there are slightly more Muslim Africans than Christian Africans in Xiaobei.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The nerve center of the area is Baohan Straight Street where there are African orientated shops and restaurants.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The street was repaved in 2015 and many of the hawkers have departed or set up shops.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] About 3 kilometres (2 mi) from Xiaobei and north of the Guangzhou railway station is Guangyuanxi, a more business orientated area with a major presence of Nigerian Igbo people.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The area is filled with large trademarts selling shoes, clothing, and other goods.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The trademarts are housed in large buildings called Tong Tong Trade Mart, Tian'en Clothing Market, Tangqi Building, Canaan Market, and Ying Fu Building.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Since stricter immigration enforcement in the summer of 2013, this area has become much more dormant than before.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Since China's economic boom in the 1990s, thousands of Africans migrated to China; most of these migrants were from West Africa.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Many Africans left Indonesia and Thailand and went to Guangzhou after the 1997 Asian financial crisis, and the economic opportunity attracted more.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In Guangzhou, Africans are generally engaged in commerce, visiting or residing in the city because of its wholesale trading markets supplied by nearby factories.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] During the 2000s, the city's African population rapidly increased with a 2008 news report stating the number of African residents had increased by 30% to 40% annually.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Since 2004, illegal immigration enforcement has become an increasing focus for police authorities in Guangzhou and other parts of China.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In 2003, campaigns against illegal immigration were conducted in Guangdong and elsewhere, and by 2008, police launched a series of "hurricane" campaigns targeting visa overstayers in the province.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In Guangzhou, a local regulation adopted in 2004 encouraged residents to report suspected cases of illegal immigration, offering cash rewards of CN¥100 for confirmed tips.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Conflict between the African community and police in Guangzhou resulted in riots in 2009 and 2012.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In July 2009, two Nigerian men jumped several floors from a building in an attempt to flee Chinese immigration authorities.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] But on hearing rumors of their deaths, hundreds of Africans, mostly Nigerian, surrounded a local police station.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The demonstration escalated into a riot that shut down eight lanes of traffic on a major thoroughfare for several hours.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In June 2012, an African held in police custody after a taxi fare dispute died after "suddenly losing consciousness", according to police.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Over a hundred Africans gathered at the police station in question demanding to know the cause of death.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] A large scale immigration enforcement sweep was conducted by local police in July and August 2013.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] A newspaper source described as a "senior government official" in Uganda blamed the Ministry of Internal Affairs for illegally selling Ugandan passports.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] A spokesperson for the Directorate of Citizenship and Immigration Control, under the Ministry of Internal Affairs, responded that the Ugandan passports were stolen or sold by Ugandan individuals.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] During the COVID-19 pandemic in mainland China, reports became widespread of Africans of Guangzhou being evicted from flats and hotels by landlords, and having difficulty in finding food and shelter as a result.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Some became homeless and had to sleep on the street.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] On 11 April, the United States Consulate General in Guangzhou warned African-Americans to avoid travel to the Guangzhou city, with a report by some African-Americans that "some businesses and hotels refuse to do business with them".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The Consulate further raised a travel warning to announce the discrimination condition against African-Americans in Guangzhou on 13 April.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In that warning, it said that Chinese officials might require Africans to participate in the COVID-19 test and undergo a 14-day supervised quarantine at their own expense.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Ambassadors in China from many African countries wrote to Foreign Minister of the People's Republic of China, Wang Yi, for asking China to resolve the discrimination problem against Africans in Guangzhou.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The chair of African Union Commission, Moussa Faki Mahamat, also summoned Chinese Ambassador to the AU, Liu Yuxi, to express his extreme concern.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] He also said in the regular press conference on 13 April that China will address the "African friends' concerns" by adopting a series of measures to avoid racist and discrimination problems, and condemned "the US had better focus on domestic efforts to contain the spread of the virus.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Attempts to use the pandemic to drive a wedge between China and Africa are bound to fail".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] By 2024, trade activity in Guangzhou by African businessmen was pre-pandemic levels.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In May 2025, public concern over immigration enforcement resurfaced when social media rumors claimed that over 3,000 police officers had raided Sanyuanli Subdistrict, a neighborhood with a large African community, in a mass crackdown on undocumented migrants.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The Sanyuanli Subdistrict government denied the allegations, describing them as "false and baseless rumors" and clarified that the heightened police presence was related to urban redevelopment projects, not immigration enforcement.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] It also characterized the claim of "3,000 officers" as an exaggeration.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] By 2014, there had been multiple marriages between African and Chinese people in Guangzhou, with almost all marriages being between African men and Chinese women.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Chinese marriage visas do not legally allow the spouse to work.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Many marriages have stability issues due to the difficulties in keeping visas.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The majority of the Chinese who live and marry Africans in Guangzhou, for example, come from the rural poorer provinces Sichuan, Hunan, Hubei.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] From 2010 to 2014, rural Chinese who married Africans and foreigners were allowed to have multiple children, unlike average Chinese citizens.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In addition to immigration enforcement, another difficulty to navigate for African traders has been the depreciation of several African currencies after the fall in oil prices since 2014.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Nigerian traders who are a large part of the African contingent reported being stymied by the difficulty of obtaining foreign currency in Nigeria needed to purchase goods.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The Nigerian government had initially reacted to the sharp depreciation in the Nigerian naira by limiting access to foreign exchange and refusing to devalue the official exchange rate.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In order to obtain naira, Nigerian traders had to resort to the black market to buy dollars at a 75% premium, making it difficult to turn a profit.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The foreign exchange problem proved so discouraging that one long time Nigerian clothing trader in Guangzhou interviewed by the *Financial Times* reported being unable to fill a single container halfway into the year in 2016.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Difficulties were reported by traders with foreign exchange in other African countries including Angola, another top oil producer.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] More recently, these challenges have intensified.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Nigeria's ongoing currency instability and restrictions on official access to dollars have led traders to rely on informal naira–RMB networks and cryptocurrency to finance trade with China.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Many traders say that bank-mediated transfers are no longer viable.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] According to one Igbo trader: "For us, it would be better to exchange naira directly with RMB; then 10,000,000 naira can buy one container.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The naira's rapid depreciation (plummeting by more than 70% between 2022 and 2024) along with a low uptake of official currency swap programs, has left most Nigerian importers dependent on unofficial payment channels to settle trade with Chinese suppliers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Traders frequently cited delays, limited availability, and bureaucratic opacity at Central Bank of Nigeria forex windows.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In some cases, traders' efforts to wire USD or RMB through the banking system were blocked, prompting them to turn to stablecoins like USDT, despite regulatory crackdowns.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Crime involving African nationals in Guangzhou has been a subject of concern among both African and Chinese.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In August 2013, the Guangzhou Municipal Public Security Bureau carried out a major anti-drug operation involving 1,300 police officers who raided the Lihua (Dragon) Hotel in the city's Yuexiu District, a known center of activity for African migrants.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The raid coincided with a broader immigration enforcement crackdown that summer and resulted in the arrest of 168 suspects, most of whom were described by police as citizens of Nigeria and Mali.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Following the raid, the Nigerian Ambassador to China at the time, Sola Onadipe, issued a highly critical public rebuke of his compatriots.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In an interview with Vanguard, he lamented the scale of involvement by Nigerians in illegal activities in China.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] He added that some Nigerians in China smoked marijuana openly and drank heavily, calling such behavior "ridiculous" and expressing personal frustration at representing them diplomatically.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] The ambassador also drew a pointed contrast with other African nationals, stating that citizens of Ghana, Cameroon, and Côte d'Ivoire did not face the same level of scrutiny from Chinese police, suggesting that Nigerians' conduct may have invited disproportionate enforcement.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] This unusually harsh rhetoric from a sitting ambassador prompted scholarly commentary.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Jackson interpreted the tirade as not just an expression of diplomatic frustration but possibly a reflection of deeper ethnic and class tensions within Nigeria.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] He noted that many Nigerians in Guangzhou are of Igbo origin from southeastern Nigeria, while Ambassador Onadipe is likely Yoruba, from the southwest.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] Jackson observed that "ambassadors are usually diplomatic and even-handed in their advocacy for their own citizens," but Onadipe's statements may have revealed latent divisions within the Nigerian state itself.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/africans-in-guangzhou] In 2017, a Nigerian consulate official in Guangzhou estimated that on average, 1% of Nigerians arriving in the city were arrested for drug-related offenses.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The American restaurant chain McDonald's has been criticised for numerous aspects of its business, including the health effects of its products, its treatment of employees, the environmental impact of its operations, and other business practices.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 1990, activists from a small group known as London Greenpeace (no connection to the international group Greenpeace) distributed leaflets entitled *What's wrong with McDonald's?*, criticizing its environmental, health, and labor record.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The corporation wrote to the group demanding they desist and apologize, and, when two of the activists refused to back down, sued them for libel leading to the "McLibel case", one of the longest cases in English civil law.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] A documentary film of the McLibel Trial has been shown in several countries.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2001, Eric Schlosser's book *Fast Food Nation* included criticism of the business practices of McDonald's.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Among the critiques were allegations that McDonald's (along with other companies within the fast food industry) uses its political influence to increase its profits at the expense of people's health and the social conditions of its workers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The book also brought into question McDonald's advertisement techniques in which it targets children.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] While the book did mention other fast-food chains, it focused primarily on McDonald's.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2002, vegetarian groups, largely Hindu and Buddhist, successfully sued McDonald's for misrepresenting its French fries as vegetarian, when they contained beef broth.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In the same year, Spanish band Ska-P released a song titled "McDollar" in their album *¡¡Que Corra La Voz!!* criticizing McDonald's.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Morgan Spurlock's 2004 documentary film *Super Size Me* claimed that McDonald's food was contributing to the increase of obesity in society and that the company was failing to provide nutritional information about its food for its customers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Six weeks after the film premiered, McDonald's announced that it was eliminating the super size option, and was creating the adult Happy Meal.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] A counter-documentary called *Fat Head* purported to point out inconsistencies in *Super Size Me*.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In response to public pressure, McDonald's has sought to include more healthy choices in its menu and has introduced a new slogan to its recruitment posters: "Not bad for a McJob".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The word McJob, first attested in the mid-1980s and later popularized by Canadian novelist Douglas Coupland in his book *Generation X: Tales for an Accelerated Culture*, has become a buzzword for low-paid, unskilled work with few prospects or benefits and little security.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's disputes this definition of McJob.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2007, the company launched an advertising campaign with the slogan "Would you like a career with that?" on Irish television, asserting that its jobs have good prospects.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In an effort to respond to growing consumer awareness of food provenance, the fast-food chain changed its supplier of both coffee beans and milk.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] UK chief executive Steve Easterbrook said: "British consumers are increasingly interested in the quality, sourcing, and ethics of the food and drink they buy".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In a bid to tap into the ethical consumer market, McDonald's switched to using coffee beans taken from stocks that are certified by the Rainforest Alliance, a conservation group.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Additionally, in response to pressure, McDonald's UK started using organic milk supplies for its bottled milk and hot drinks, although it still uses conventional milk in its milkshakes, and in all of its dairy products in the United States.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] According to a report published by *Farmers Weekly* in 2007, the quantity of milk used by McDonald's could have accounted for as much as 5 percent of the UK's organic milk output.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's announced in May 2008 that, in the United States and Canada, it has switched to using cooking oil that contains no trans fats for its french fries, and canola-based oil with corn and soy oils, for its baked items, pies and cookies, by the end of 2018.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Though the company objected, the term "McJob" was added to *Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary* in 2003.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The term was defined as "a low-paying job that requires little skill and provides little opportunity for advancement".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Merriam-Webster's Unabridged Dictionary also contains the word "McMansion", a critical, pejorative term used to describe an overly large, ostentatious, sometimes poorly designed or constructed house, often found in a suburb or in new developments on traditionally rural land.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McMansions are often built in multiples that are difficult to distinguish from one another, like assembly-line factory parts or fast-food hamburgers.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2006, an unsanctioned *McDonald's Video Game* by Italian group Molleindustria was released online.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] It is a parody of the business practices of the corporate giant, taking the guise of a tycoon style business simulation game.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In the game, the player plays the role of a McDonald's CEO, choosing whether or not to use controversial practices like genetically altered cow feed, plowing over rainforests, and corrupting public officials.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's issued a statement distancing itself from the game.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In January 2014, McDonald's was accused of having used a series of tax maneuvers to avoid taxes in France.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] French authorities have fined McDonald's France in 2016 300 million euros for unpaid taxes on profit.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In October 2020, the Azerbaijan branch of McDonald's was criticized for Facebook and Instagram posts endorsing Azerbaijan's military actions against Armenia in Nagorno-Karabakh.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] While McDonald's restaurants exist in Armenia, as of January 2020, none of them were franchises of the global chain.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] June 2023 saw McDonald's receive scrutiny for removing and replacing content on the fan-run McDonald's Wiki on Fandom with advertising.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The company paid Fandom an undisclosed amount to temporarily replace the page about Grimace, which originally detailed the history of the character, into an advertisement promoting the chain's Grimace Shake.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The decision was vocally protested by Nathan Steinmetz, author of the Grimace article, arguing that the effort he placed into sourcing and writing the article was thrown down the drain in order to promote the product.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In April 2024, a McDonald's in Nantong, China apologized to a customer after the word "*shǎbī*" was written on his receipt for a refund.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] They assured the employee responsible has been reprimanded, and promised to improve staff training and customer service procedures.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Although McDonald's has a policy against abuse of staff, reports in the UK have shown numerous cases of sexual and racial abuse by managers towards younger employees.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Since McDonald's began receiving criticism for its environmental practices in the 1970s, it has significantly reduced its use of materials.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] For instance, an "average meal" in the 1970s—a Big Mac, fries, and a drink—required 46 grams (1.6 oz) of packaging; today, it requires 25 grams (0.88 oz), a 46 percent reduction.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In addition, McDonald's eliminated the need for intermediate containers for cola by using a delivery system that pumps syrup directly from the delivery truck into storage containers, saving two million pounds (910 tonnes) of packaging annually.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Weight reductions in packaging and products, as well as increased usage of bulk packaging, ultimately decreased packaging by twenty-four million pounds (11,000 tonnes) annually.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's efforts to reduce solid waste by using less packaging and by promoting the use of recycled materials were recognized by the U.S.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In April 2008, McDonald's announced that 11 of its restaurants in Sheffield, England, were engaged in a biomass trial program that cut its waste and carbon footprint by half in the area.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In this trial, waste from the restaurants was collected by Veolia Environmental Services and used to produce energy at a power plant.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's announced plans to expand this project, although the lack of biomass power plants in the United States would prevent adoption of this plan as a national standard there anytime soon.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In addition, in Europe, McDonald's has been recycling vegetable grease by converting it to fuel for its diesel trucks.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In an effort to reduce energy usage by 25 percent in its restaurants, McDonald's opened a prototype restaurant in Chicago in 2009, intending to use the model in its other restaurants throughout the world.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2012, McDonald's announced they would trial replacing styrofoam coffee cups with an alternative material.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2018, McDonalds switched from plastic straws to paper ones in Ireland and the United Kingdom and Australia in an effort to reduce plastic pollution.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The Netherlands followed suit in 2020, so did Germany in 2021.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In January 2021, McDonald's Arcos Dorados, the largest independent McDonald's franchise in the world which operates stores in Latin America and the Caribbean, introduced food trays manufactured by UBQ Materials that use a mix of food waste by-products to reduce the use of virgin plastic.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's uses a corn-based bioplastic to produce containers for some products.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The environmental benefits of this technology are controversial, with critics noting that biodegradation is slow and produces greenhouse gases, and that contamination of traditional plastic waste streams with bioplastics can complicate recycling efforts.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Studies of litter have found that McDonald's is one of the most littered brands worldwide.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2012, a Keep Australia Beautiful study found that McDonald's was the most littered brand in Queensland.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2009, Keep Britain Tidy likewise found McDonald's to be the leading producer of fast-food litter on British streets, accounting for 29% of the total.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] An early protest against this practice was "Operation Send-It-Back", launched by London Greenpeace in 1994 in response to the company's targeting of activists in the McLibel Trial.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Participants in Operation Send-It-Back returned 30 sacks of McDonald's litter to the company.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In the 2010s, similar individual protests took place in New Zealand and England.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's has been the subject of animal rights activism.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2021, Animal Rising blockaded four UK distribution centers using bamboo towers, leading to food shortages at restaurants.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] They cited "suffering of animals" in the McDonald's supply chain as a motivating factor.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] During the Gaza war, amidst the Israeli blockade of supplies in Gaza, McDonald's in Israel was condemned after giving free food to the Israel Defense Forces who were accused of committing war crimes against Palestinians.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The hashtag #BoycottMcDonalds gained worldwide traction on social media.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] There were also large gathering outside restaurants in Lebanon and Egypt protesting the move.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonalds in other countries like Turkey and Pakistan, distanced themselves from the Israeli brand.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In January 2024, McDonald's CEO Chris Kempczinski acknowledged the backlash, stating, "Several markets in the Middle East and some outside the region are experiencing a meaningful business impact due to the war and associated misinformation that is affecting brands like McDonald's".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In April 2024, McDonald's reached a deal with the Israeli franchisee, Alonyal, to buy back all 225 outlets to the corporation.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's has been involved in a number of lawsuits and other legal cases, most of which involved trademark disputes.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The company has threatened many food businesses with legal action unless it drops the Mc or Mac from trading names.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In April 2007, in Perth, Western Australia, McDonald's pleaded guilty to five charges relating to the employment of children under 15 in one of its outlets and was fined A$8,000.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The EUIPO ruled in Supermac's favour, finding that McDonald's "has not proven genuine use" of many trademarks, cancelling McDonald's owned trademarks such as "Big Mac" and certain "Mc"-related trademarks within the European Union.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] Burger King responded by "trolling" McDonald's by giving their sandwiches names that included the words "Big Mac", that also mocked the original burger, which included, "Like a Big Mac But Juicier", "Like a Big Mac, But Actually Big" and "Big Mac-ish But Flame-Grilled of Course".
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] On September 8, 2009, McDonald's Malaysian operations lost a lawsuit to prevent another restaurant calling itself McCurry.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's lost in an appeal to Malaysia's highest court, the Federal Court.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] On December 29, 2016, McDonald's Malaysia issued a statement that said only certified halal cakes are allowed inside its restaurants nationwide.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The longest-running legal action of all time in the UK was the McLibel case against two defendants who criticized a number of aspects of the company.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The trial lasted 10 years and called 130 witnesses.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The European Court of Human Rights deemed that the unequal resources of the litigants breached the defendants rights to freedom of speech and biased the trial.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The result was widely seen as a "PR disaster" for McDonald's.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] McDonald's Restaurants* examined a McDonald's practice of serving coffee so hot that when spilled, it caused third degree burns requiring weeks of hospitalization and skin grafting surgery.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The trial outcome was an award of $2.86 million (equivalent to $5.47 million in 2024) for the plaintiff, 81-year old Stella Liebeck.
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] The amount was later reduced to $640,000 (equivalent to $1.2 million in 2024).
[src:criticism-of-mcdonald-s/criticism-of-mcdonald-s] In 2019, a McDonald's employee, Jenna Ries, sued the restaurant chain over allowing sexual harassment in the work place and described the working environment as "toxic".
